---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import certData from '../data/certifications.json';
---

<Base title="About" description="Why bigcompute.science exists, how it was built, and how to contribute">
  <section class="about-page">
    <h1 class="m-reveal">About</h1>

    <p class="tagline m-reveal"><strong>Big math</strong> &mdash; computational mathematics at scales requiring specialized hardware. GPU clusters, custom CUDA kernels, and serious engineering applied to open conjectures that nobody else is computing.</p>

    <h2 class="m-reveal">What This Is</h2>

    <p>bigcompute.science is an open computational lab notebook. We run expensive GPU experiments on open mathematical conjectures &mdash; Zaremba, Ramsey R(5,5), Kronecker coefficients, class numbers, Hausdorff spectra &mdash; and publish everything: the code, the raw data, the findings, and the full audit trail.</p>

    <p>Every finding is AI-audited claim-by-claim against published literature by multiple models from multiple providers. Currently: <strong>{certData.stats.total_reviews} reviews</strong> from <strong>{certData.stats.unique_models} AI models</strong> across <strong>{certData.stats.unique_providers} providers</strong>. {certData.stats.issues_discovered} issues identified, {certData.stats.issues_fixed} resolved &mdash; each fix linked to its commit.</p>

    <p>This is not peer-reviewed mathematics. The safest way to describe our results is: <em>computed, archived, benchmarked, observed</em> &mdash; not <em>proved</em>.</p>

    <h2 class="m-reveal">How It Was Built</h2>

    <p>The project evolved through sustained human&ndash;AI collaboration. The human provides mathematical direction and judgment. The AI generates code, cross-references literature, and iterates tirelessly. The result is infrastructure neither could have built alone.</p>

    <p>The timeline of how it came together:</p>

    <div class="timeline m-reveal">
      <div class="tl-item"><span class="tl-phase">Phase 1</span><span class="tl-desc">GPU experiments &mdash; CUDA kernels for Zaremba verification (210B denominators), Ramsey R(5,5) (4.4T extensions checked), Kronecker S<sub>30</sub> (26.4B triples), class numbers (30B discriminants), Hausdorff spectrum (1M subsets).</span></div>
      <div class="tl-item"><span class="tl-phase">Phase 2</span><span class="tl-desc">Findings &mdash; 15 computational findings extracted from experiment data. Each with structured frontmatter, reproduction commands, dataset links.</span></div>
      <div class="tl-item"><span class="tl-phase">Phase 3</span><span class="tl-desc">AI peer review &mdash; Every finding reviewed by Claude Opus 4.6 (Anthropic), o3-pro (OpenAI), Grok (xAI), and GPT-5.2 (OpenAI). Real errors found: a prime count was wrong (669&rarr;172), a proof had circular logic, a spectral bound needed caveats.</span></div>
      <div class="tl-item"><span class="tl-phase">Phase 4</span><span class="tl-desc">Remediation &mdash; 92 issues tracked with severity, status, and commit-linked resolutions. Proof framework rewritten. Spectral bound interval-certified with 77 digits of arb ball arithmetic.</span></div>
      <div class="tl-item"><span class="tl-phase">Phase 5</span><span class="tl-desc">Infrastructure &mdash; Review scripts, manifest system, autonomous research agent, MCP server (23 tools), Colab notebooks with GPU auto-detect. The agent runs the full cycle: monitor &rarr; harvest &rarr; analyze &rarr; review &rarr; remediate &rarr; deploy.</span></div>
      <div class="tl-item"><span class="tl-phase">Phase 6</span><span class="tl-desc">Distributed compute &mdash; Anyone with a browser can open a Colab notebook, auto-compile CUDA kernels for their free T4 GPU, and run experiments on open conjectures. Results submitted via PR.</span></div>
    </div>

    <p>The entire website &mdash; every finding, every review, every badge, every commit link &mdash; is generated from data. The verification page reads from <code>certifications.json</code>. The MCP server reads from <code>manifest.json</code>. The changelog reads from <code>git log</code>. When the research agent runs, everything updates automatically.</p>

    <h2 class="m-reveal">Why This Matters</h2>

    <p>Heavy GPU computation produces results that are expensive to reproduce. We publish everything so the work compounds rather than gets repeated. If an AI agent needs to know whether Zaremba's conjecture holds for d up to 200 billion &mdash; that answer exists here, verified, with the code to reproduce it.</p>

    <p>We believe computational results should be:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Open</strong> &mdash; all code, data, methodology, and reviews published</li>
      <li><strong>Structured</strong> &mdash; machine-readable for agent consumption (MCP, llms.txt, frontmatter)</li>
      <li><strong>Reproducible</strong> &mdash; exact commands to verify every result</li>
      <li><strong>Honest</strong> &mdash; overclaims caught and corrected publicly, with commit links</li>
      <li><strong>Auditable</strong> &mdash; every claim reviewed by multiple AI models, every issue tracked</li>
      <li><strong>Verified</strong> &mdash; community submissions re-run on our GPUs to confirm authenticity</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="m-reveal">Community Verification</h2>

    <p>Anyone can contribute computational results via <a href="/interactive/">Colab notebooks</a> running on free T4 GPUs. But how do we know the results are real? We <strong>trust but verify</strong>: every new submission is automatically re-run on our cluster. If the numbers match, it's labeled <code>verified</code>. If they don't, it's flagged.</p>

    <p>Submissions are free. Verification costs GPU time. That's what <a href="https://guerrillamathematics.com">Guerrilla Mathematics&trade;</a> funds &mdash; every purchase buys cluster time for verifying community results and running new experiments on unsolved problems.</p>

    <h2 class="m-reveal">For Students and Researchers</h2>

    <p>This project exists to make open mathematical problems more accessible through computation.</p>

    <p>When I run large computations on open conjectures &mdash; checking billions of cases, searching for patterns, exhausting difficult examples &mdash; the goal is not to replace mathematical proof. It is to <strong>close in</strong>. Every narrowed bound, every observed pattern, every verified range makes the remaining problem more tractable and, hopefully, more exciting. Seeing a decades-old conjecture with fresh computational evidence can inspire approaches that pure theory alone might not suggest.</p>

    <p>These problems are more than academic curiosities. Number theory underlies cryptography. Spectral theory drives signal processing. Combinatorics informs algorithm design. Representation theory connects to quantum information. These ideas underlie much of applied mathematics, computer science, and the foundations of AI. A conjecture about continued fractions may seem abstract, but the techniques developed along the way become tools for the next generation of problems.</p>

    <p>I encourage students &mdash; undergraduate, graduate, or ambitious high school students &mdash; to use this data as a starting point for real research. Pick a pattern. Try to explain it. Formalize it. Extend it. Prove it. The computational results are here, open and reproducible. The theoretical work &mdash; the real mathematics &mdash; is yours to do.</p>

    <p>A note on tools: <strong>do not let convention limit your approach.</strong> Some of the next advances may come from those who combine mathematical insight with modern computational tools &mdash; GPUs, AI assistants, formal verification, automated search. Learning how to think mathematically matters more than any particular technique. Patterns, structures, how truths transfer between domains, how logic composes &mdash; these are the durable skills. Specific methods come and go. The ability to recognize structure does not.</p>

    <p>This site is for anyone with curiosity and hardware: students writing theses, engineers with idle GPU clusters, researchers exploring adjacent fields, or anyone who thinks open problems deserve open computation. This is not an authority. It is a place to share computational results as openly and transparently as possible.</p>

    <h2 class="m-reveal">Contribute</h2>

    <p>Three ways in, ordered by effort:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Open a Colab notebook</strong> &mdash; free T4 GPU, auto-compile, run an experiment, download results. <a href="/interactive/">Get started &rarr;</a></li>
      <li><strong>Run the research agent</strong> &mdash; clone the repo, set one API key (Gemini free, or OpenAI, or Anthropic), run <code>./scripts/run_agent.sh</code>. <a href="https://github.com/cahlen/idontknow/blob/main/AGENTS.md">Guide &rarr;</a></li>
      <li><strong>Submit a review or computation</strong> &mdash; write a review JSON per our <a href="https://github.com/cahlen/idontknow/blob/main/docs/verifications/SCHEMA.md">schema</a>, or upload raw data to your own HF dataset and link it via PR.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2 class="m-reveal">Technical Stack</h2>

    <div class="stack-grid m-reveal">
      <div class="stack-item"><strong>Compute</strong><br/>8&times;B200 DGX (1.43 TB VRAM) + RTX 5090</div>
      <div class="stack-item"><strong>Experiments</strong><br/>Custom CUDA kernels, Python harnesses</div>
      <div class="stack-item"><strong>Reviews</strong><br/>{certData.stats.unique_models} AI models, {certData.stats.unique_providers} providers, manifest-driven</div>
      <div class="stack-item"><strong>Website</strong><br/>Astro + KaTeX, Cloudflare Pages</div>
      <div class="stack-item"><strong>MCP Server</strong><br/>23 tools, no auth, Cloudflare Worker</div>
      <div class="stack-item"><strong>Data</strong><br/>Hugging Face datasets, GitHub, CC BY 4.0</div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="m-reveal">Who</h2>

    <div class="who-section m-reveal">
      <img src="https://cdn-avatars.huggingface.co/v1/production/uploads/64495e3c958a6aca061119f2/-D9CURxArrhYAc9oFdsO6.png" alt="Cahlen Humphreys" class="profile-pic" />
      <div>
        <p>
          <a href="https://github.com/cahlen">Cahlen Humphreys</a> &mdash; Managing Principal at <a href="https://www.enfuse.io">Enfuse.io</a>, speaker at NVIDIA GTC, and builder of things that require too many GPUs. M.S. Mathematics, Florida Atlantic University. B.S. Mathematics, Boise State University. Research interests include continued fraction neural networks (<a href="https://github.com/cahlen/cofrgenet-f">CoFrGeNet-F</a>), formal theorem proving with LLMs, and computational number theory. Based in Irvine, CA.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      <a href="https://x.com/cahlenhumphreys">X</a> &middot; <a href="https://huggingface.co/cahlen">Hugging Face</a> &middot; <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/cahlenhu">LinkedIn</a>
    </p>

    <div class="collab-note m-reveal">
      <p>This project was produced through human&ndash;AI collaboration. The human provides direction, judgment, and mathematical taste. The AI provides code generation, literature cross-referencing, and tireless iteration. Every page on this site discloses this collaboration. The AI models used include Claude Opus 4.6 (Anthropic), o3-pro (OpenAI), GPT-5.2 (OpenAI), and Grok (xAI).</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script is:inline>
  (function() {
    var reveals = document.querySelectorAll('.m-reveal');
    function onScroll() {
      var vh = window.innerHeight;
      for (var i = 0; i < reveals.length; i++) {
        var el = reveals[i];
        if (el.getBoundingClientRect().top < vh * 0.85) el.classList.add('visible');
      }
    }
    window.addEventListener('scroll', onScroll, { passive: true });
    onScroll();
  })();
  </script>

  <style>
    .m-reveal { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(20px); transition: opacity 0.7s ease, transform 0.7s ease; }
    .m-reveal.visible { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }

    .tagline { font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--text-secondary); margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }

    .timeline {
      margin: 1.5rem 0;
      padding-left: 1.2rem;
      border-left: 2px solid rgba(232,196,122,0.2);
    }
    .tl-item {
      padding: 0.5rem 0 0.5rem 1rem;
      position: relative;
    }
    .tl-item::before {
      content: '';
      position: absolute;
      left: -1.45rem;
      top: 0.75rem;
      width: 8px;
      height: 8px;
      background: #e8c47a;
      border-radius: 50%;
    }
    .tl-phase {
      display: inline-block;
      font-family: var(--font-mono, 'JetBrains Mono', monospace);
      font-size: 0.7rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      color: #e8c47a;
      margin-right: 0.6rem;
      min-width: 4rem;
    }
    .tl-desc {
      font-size: 0.85rem;
      color: var(--text-secondary);
      line-height: 1.5;
    }

    .stack-grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
      gap: 0.8rem;
      margin: 1.2rem 0;
    }
    .stack-item {
      padding: 0.8rem;
      background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--surface, #1a1a1a) 60%, transparent);
      border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--border, #333) 40%, transparent);
      border-radius: 6px;
      font-size: 0.8rem;
      color: var(--text-secondary);
      line-height: 1.4;
    }
    .stack-item strong { color: #e8c47a; display: block; margin-bottom: 0.2rem; font-size: 0.72rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em; }

    .collab-note {
      margin-top: 2rem;
      padding: 1rem 1.2rem;
      background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--surface, #1a1a1a) 50%, transparent);
      border-left: 3px solid rgba(232,196,122,0.3);
      border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0;
    }
    .collab-note p {
      font-size: 0.82rem;
      color: var(--text-secondary);
      line-height: 1.6;
      margin: 0;
      font-style: italic;
    }

    @media (max-width: 600px) {
      .stack-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    }
  </style>
</Base>
